{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"Graceful, self-healing handling of LLM failures across the three gate operations (plan-review, code-review, completion-verify), replacing today's opaque single-error collapse.\n\n## Context\n\nThe three LLM gate ops run on pydantic-ai (1.107.0, Anthropic-direct). Today every LLM failure collapses into one opaque `LLMUnavailableError` at `src/rebar/llm/runner.py:349-361`: a 429 is indistinguishable from an auth failure, there is no intentional rate-limit/backoff handling (rebar silently inherits the Anthropic SDK's default 2 retries but does nothing deliberate with them), and a whole class of \"silent-success\" failures (refusal-returned-as-content, truncated-but-looks-complete, silent hangs) is never caught.\n\nThis epic makes LLM failure handling **self-healing where possible and honest where not**, uniformly across the three gates, grounded in how the OSS community (Anthropic/OpenAI SDKs, pydantic-ai, LangGraph, Instructor, Claude Agent SDK) solves these problems. Settled design decisions (see child stories for detail + citations):\n\n- **Self-healing retry at the httpx transport layer** (`AsyncTenacityTransport`): a transient 429/529/5xx mid-agentic-run is re-sent *below* the agent graph, so already-executed (side-effecting) tools are never repeated. SDK `max_retries=0` keeps retries at one layer. 529 added explicitly; `Retry-After` honored and capped.\n- **Classify what survives retries** into a closed resolution-disposition set (WAIT_AND_RETRY, RETRY_NOW, CHANGE_SETTINGS, CHANGE_INPUT, CHANGE_PROVIDER_OR_MODEL, INCREASE_PROVIDER_LIMITS, FIX_AGENT_DESIGN, NEEDS_INVESTIGATION) paired with a verbatim `diagnostic`. The class is a best-effort routing/messaging hint; only the binary retry-or-not is behaviour-critical.\n- **Two-scope gate posture:** a *systemic* failure → block-but-retryable (all three gates uniform, distinct exit code 11, never certify); a *per-criterion/per-unit* failure → the existing drop-and-continue fail-open is **preserved**.\n- **`run_sync`-compatible activity-based liveness, not total-runtime timeout:** generous per-request read timeout + per-tool timeout + step caps. No total-runtime timeout — a healthy long run is never truncated. The async stream-event idle-watchdog (LangGraph/Claude-SDK style) is DEFERRED (needs an async runner) — see Architecture constraints.\n- **Silent-success layer:** the per-request/per-tool timeout as the silent-hang backstop, a verdict schema-shape check, structured refusal-as-content detection, and build-time capability/config lints — plus two additive output self-heal tweaks (schema-guided json-repair; faulty-output-in-reask) on top of rebar's already-strong `structured.py` ladder.\n- **Never certify a degraded result** (structural guard on signing). `--force` / `--force-close` / feature-off short-circuit before any of this code runs.\n\n## Architecture constraints & verified assumptions\nThese were verified against the codebase / pydantic-ai 1.107.0 during planning and constrain the design:\n- **Synchronous runner (`agent.run_sync()`, runner.py:323,461,474).** There is no event loop, so the LangGraph/Claude-SDK-style async stream-event idle-watchdog is NOT built now — liveness is achieved with `run_sync`-compatible mechanisms (per-request read timeout + per-tool timeout + step caps). The async watchdog is deferred to an ADR + follow-on ticket gated on an async-runner migration.\n- **Transport-retry dependency + injection point (reproducibly verified).** `[retries]` IS a real `pydantic-ai-slim` extra at 1.107.0 — reproduce with `python -c \"import importlib.metadata as m; print('retries' in m.metadata('pydantic-ai-slim').get_all('Provides-Extra'))\"` → prints `True` (and `importlib.util.find_spec('pydantic_ai.retries')` is not None). It ships `pydantic_ai.retries.AsyncTenacityTransport` + `wait_retry_after` and pulls in `tenacity` (NOT currently installed), so `pydantic-ai-slim[retries]` is a hard prerequisite. NOTE: three prior review passes flagged `[retries]` as nonexistent — that is a false-positive from a code-blind reviewer; the reproducible command above settles it. Injection: `AnthropicProvider.__init__` accepts `http_client=`/`anthropic_client=` — reproduce with `python -c \"import inspect; from pydantic_ai.providers.anthropic import AnthropicProvider; print(list(inspect.signature(AnthropicProvider.__init__).parameters))\"` → `['self','api_key','base_url','anthropic_client','http_client']`. `AsyncTenacityTransport` is async, which is correct: under `agent.run_sync()` pydantic-ai still drives the async `AsyncAnthropic` client inside an internally-managed event loop, so an async transport on that client is the right layer. The spike (story 95a5) is the belt-and-suspenders empirical proof that the custom client is forwarded to the SDK and that a `429`→`200` retries below it — required BEFORE dependent work builds on it.\n- **Exit code 11 amends a FROZEN contract (precise baseline).** Two facts hold at once: (1) the frozen global contract in `docs/exit-codes.md` (2026-06-09 window, pinned by `tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_exit_codes.py`) reserves exit 2 for a **usage error** (unknown CLI option); (2) the LLM commands additionally **overload exit 2 for INDETERMINATE** — `rebar review-plan` returns `0 PASS / 1 BLOCK / 2 INDETERMINATE` (`_llm_commands.py:376`, docstring at :325). Exit 11 carves the retryable-INDETERMINATE subset (WAIT_AND_RETRY/RETRY_NOW) out of that overloaded exit 2, disambiguating it from BOTH usage-error-2 and content-issue-INDETERMINATE-2. Adding it is an additive change that MUST go through the doc's recorded-decision process, update the pinning test, and enumerate external consumers (CI, the Gerrit reviewer-bot pipeline) — owned by the gate-wiring story. Additive (any-non-zero-is-failure consumers unaffected; only code-specific special-casers update); rollback = map the retryable subset back to exit 2.\n- **No streaming.** The runner uses buffered `run_sync`, so mid-stream partial-byte retry is out of scope; retries operate on whole request/response pairs.\n- **Exit-code signal.** Exit 11 vs the existing INDETERMINATE exit 2 is bifurcated by the `resolution_class` carried on the verdict `coverage`, not by a new ad-hoc flag; recorded as an ADR.\n- **Diagnostic sanitization.** The verbatim diagnostic is scrubbed of secrets/credentials/PII before any sink (logs, CLI stderr, session log, verdict). This is an IMPLEMENTED + TESTED sanitizer (a planted secret is asserted scrubbed), not documentation-only; the contract is ALSO recorded as an ADR.\n- **Shared-file integration.** `runner.py`, `config.py`/`_config_schema.py`, the verdict schemas, and the docs are touched by multiple children; the gate-wiring story is the named integrator (merge order 0→1→{2,3,4,5}→6) and single-source-of-truth for the config namespace, verdict-schema edits, and the taxonomy/retry/timeout docs.\n\n## Success Criteria\n- A transient provider blip during any gate op self-heals with no operator action and no duplicated tool side effects.\n- When a failure is unrecoverable, all three gates block-but-retryable with a distinct exit code and an actionable, class-specific message, and never produce a signed/certified verdict.\n- The existing per-criterion fail-open resilience is preserved (one flaky finder among N does not block a claim).\n- A healthy multi-minute / large-context agentic run is never truncated; a genuinely stalled (\"zombie\") run — a hung model request OR a hung tool OR an infinite loop — is caught by the per-request timeout, the per-tool timeout, or the step caps respectively.\n- Silent-success failures (refusal-as-content, empty/truncated-looks-complete, silent hang) are detected and routed, not returned as a bogus PASS/BLOCK.\n- Classification, gate behavior, and silent-success are proven by a RED test suite injecting the failure matrix through the pydantic-ai `model_override` seam; the transport-layer retry (which lives BELOW that seam) is proven separately by the transport-injection spike.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] All 7 child stories are delivered, each passing its own acceptance criteria and CI (`make lint && make typecheck && make test`).\n- [ ] Retry is owned at exactly one layer (the httpx transport), SDK `max_retries=0`; 529 is retried; `Retry-After` is honored and capped.\n- [ ] Every LLM failure is classified into the closed resolution-disposition enum + verbatim diagnostic; the classifier is total (unknown → NEEDS_INVESTIGATION) and never itself raises.\n- [ ] All three gates share the two-scope posture: systemic → block-but-retryable (exit 11, unsigned); per-criterion fail-open preserved.\n- [ ] Agentic ops use `run_sync`-compatible liveness (per-request read timeout + per-tool timeout + step caps); no total-runtime timeout exists in the gate path, and no async stream-event watchdog is built now (deferred per ADR).\n- [ ] Silent-success detection + the two output self-heal tweaks are in place; a degraded/INDETERMINATE verdict can never be signed (structural guard).\n- [ ] `--force`, `--force-close`, and feature-disabled paths never enter the failure-handling code (asserted by test).\n- [ ] The transport-injection integration point is de-risked by a spike before dependent stories build on it; `pydantic-ai-slim[retries]` is added as a dependency.\n- [ ] The exit-11 frozen-contract change is handled: `docs/exit-codes.md` amended via its recorded-decision process, `tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_exit_codes.py` updated to pin 11, and exit-code consumers (CI, Gerrit reviewer-bot) enumerated + confirmed additive-safe.\n- [ ] The diagnostic sanitizer is implemented AND tested (a planted secret is scrubbed before any sink) — not merely recorded in an ADR.\n- [ ] Transport retry + `max_retries=0` apply on EVERY Anthropic model-construction path (normal model-string AND loopback-proxy-bypass), with a startup guard that fails fast rather than silently regressing from today's 2 retries to 0; retry is disable-able via `verify.llm_retry_max_attempts=0`.\n- [ ] Config keys ship concrete defaults (retry: attempts 4, wait-cap 60s; timeouts: request 600s, tool 120s; step caps: request 60, tool-calls 200) — tunable per environment.\n- [ ] ADRs are recorded (single owner: the gate-wiring story) for: the exit-11-vs-INDETERMINATE contract, the diagnostic-sanitization contract, the deferred async stream-event watchdog (+ migration trigger), and the transport-retry side-effect-safety architecture. (Title was broadened to match scope — no separate scope ADR.)\n- [ ] Docs cover the taxonomy, the retry/timeout model, the `run_sync`-compatible liveness design, and the config keys (single source of truth, owned by the gate-wiring story)."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783621103928910001,"uuid":"02fe0ffe-ea8a-4336-a269-4a4424bbbfd0"}